.TH NCCLI 1 "2025" "netctl" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
nccli \- comprehensive network control command-line interface
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B nccli
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] \fICOMMAND\fR [\fIARGS\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B nccli
is a comprehensive command-line interface for network management that provides complete
network device and connection management using the netctl backend. It is modeled after
nmcli and provides similar functionality for connection and device management.
.PP
.B nccli
supports connection management, device management, WiFi operations, and multiple output
formats including terse, tabular, and multiline modes for both human and machine-readable output.
.SH COMMANDS
.SS General Commands
.TP
.B general status
Show network system status
.TP
.B general hostname [\fIHOSTNAME\fR]
Get or set system hostname
.TP
.B general permissions
Show current user capabilities
.TP
.B general logging [\fILEVEL\fR] [\fIDOMAINS\fR]
Get or set logging level and domains
.SS Networking Control
.TP
.B networking on
Enable networking (bring all interfaces up)
.TP
.B networking off
Disable networking (bring all interfaces down)
.TP
.B networking connectivity
Get network connectivity state
.SS Radio Control
.TP
.B radio all
Show all radio switches status
.TP
.B radio wifi [on|off]
Get or set WiFi radio state
.SS Connection Management
.TP
.B connection show [\fINAME\fR]
List configured connections or show details of a specific connection
.TP
.B connection up \fINAME\fR [\fIOPTIONS\fR]
Activate a connection
.TP
.B connection down \fINAME\fR
Deactivate a connection
.TP
.B connection add \fITYPE\fR \fIOPTIONS\fR
Add a new connection
.TP
.B connection modify \fINAME\fR \fIOPTIONS\fR
Modify an existing connection
.TP
.B connection edit \fINAME\fR
Edit a connection interactively
.TP
.B connection delete \fINAME\fR
Delete a connection
.TP
.B connection reload
Reload all connection files from disk
.TP
.B connection load \fIFILE\fR
Load or reload a specific connection file
.TP
.B connection import \fIFILE\fR
Import an external configuration
.TP
.B connection export \fINAME\fR \fIFILE\fR
Export a connection to a file
.TP
.B connection clone \fINAME\fR \fINEW-NAME\fR
Clone an existing connection
.SS Device Management
.TP
.B device status [\fIDEVICE\fR]
Show device status
.TP
.B device show \fIDEVICE\fR
Show detailed device information
.TP
.B device set \fIDEVICE\fR \fIPROPERTY\fR \fIVALUE\fR
Set device properties
.TP
.B device connect \fIDEVICE\fR
Connect a device
.TP
.B device reapply \fIDEVICE\fR
Reapply connection to device
.TP
.B device modify \fIDEVICE\fR \fIOPTIONS\fR
Modify active connection on device
.TP
.B device disconnect \fIDEVICE\fR
Disconnect a device
.TP
.B device delete \fIDEVICE\fR
Delete a software device
.TP
.B device monitor [\fIDEVICE\fR]
Monitor device activity
.TP
.B device lldp [\fIDEVICE\fR]
Show LLDP neighbors
.SS WiFi Device Commands
.TP
.B device wifi list [\fIDEVICE\fR]
List available WiFi access points
.TP
.B device wifi connect \fISSID\fR [--password \fIPASSWORD\fR]
Connect to a WiFi network
.TP
.B device wifi hotspot [--ssid \fISSID\fR] [--password \fIPASSWORD\fR]
Create a WiFi hotspot
.TP
.B device wifi radio [on|off]
Turn WiFi radio on or off
.SS Monitoring
.TP
.B monitor
Monitor network activity and changes
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B -t, --terse
Terse output mode (machine-readable, values separated by colons)
.TP
.B -p, --pretty
Pretty output mode (human-readable, default)
.TP
.B -m, --mode \fIMODE\fR
Output mode: tabular, multiline, or terse
.TP
.B -f, --fields \fIFIELDS\fR
Specify fields to output (comma-separated list)
.TP
.B -c, --colors \fICOLOR\fR
Use colors in output: yes, no, or auto (default: auto)
.TP
.B -h, --help
Print help information
.TP
.B -V, --version
Print version information
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/netctl/*.nctl
Connection configuration files (TOML format)
.TP
.I /usr/share/doc/netctl/examples/
Example connection configuration files
.TP
.I /run/netctl/
Runtime state directory
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Show general network status:
.EX
nccli
nccli general status
.EE
.TP
List all connections:
.EX
nccli connection show
.EE
.TP
Create a new WiFi connection:
.EX
nccli connection add --type wifi --con-name MyWiFi \\
    --ifname wlan0 --ssid "MyNetwork" --password "MyPassword" \\
    --ip4 auto
.EE
.TP
Activate a connection:
.EX
nccli connection up MyWiFi
.EE
.TP
List all devices:
.EX
nccli device status
.EE
.TP
Show detailed device information:
.EX
nccli device show wlan0
.EE
.TP
Scan for WiFi networks:
.EX
nccli device wifi list
.EE
.TP
Connect to a WiFi network:
.EX
nccli device wifi connect "NetworkName" --password "password"
.EE
.TP
Create a WiFi hotspot:
.EX
nccli device wifi hotspot --ssid "MyHotspot" \\
    --password "mypassword"
.EE
.TP
Monitor network changes:
.EX
nccli monitor
.EE
.TP
Machine-readable output:
.EX
nccli -t device status
.EE
.SH CONNECTION CONFIGURATION
Connection configuration files are stored in
.I /etc/netctl/
in TOML format with .nctl extension.
.PP
Example WiFi connection file (MyWiFi.nctl):
.EX
[connection]
name = "MyWiFi"
type = "wifi"
interface-name = "wlan0"
autoconnect = true

[wifi]
ssid = "MyNetwork"
mode = "infrastructure"

[wifi-security]
key-mgmt = "wpa-psk"
psk = "MyPassword"

[ipv4]
method = "auto"
.EE
.SH SECURITY
.SS Input Validation
.TP
.B Connection Names
Validated to prevent path traversal attacks. Only alphanumeric characters, hyphens,
underscores, and dots are allowed (maximum 64 characters).
.TP
.B WiFi SSIDs
Validated according to IEEE 802.11 standards (1-32 bytes, no control characters).
.TP
.B WiFi Passwords
Validated for WPA2/WPA3 compliance (8-63 ASCII characters).
.SS File Security
Configuration files are created with 0600 permissions (read/write for owner only).
WiFi passwords are stored in plain text in configuration files - ensure proper
file system permissions and consider using file system encryption for sensitive deployments.
.SS Access Control
Network operations require appropriate system permissions (typically root/sudo).
All commands validate input before executing system operations. Path traversal
attacks are prevented through strict validation of file paths.
